PNEUMONIA - PAKISTAN: (PUNJAB) CHILDREN, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 16 Dec 2014
Source: The News [edited]
http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-6-290366-Incidence-of-pneumonia-on-the-rise


The paediatrics departments being operated in 2 of the 3 allied hospitals in town [Rawalpindi, Punjab province] have been receiving extraordinary influx of child patients with both upper and lower respiratory tract infections particularly after a sharp fall in mercury.

Data collected by 'The News' on Monday [15 Dec 2014] reveals that well over 80 percent of the total child patients being presented to paediatrics departments in Holy Family Hospital and Benazir Bhutto Hospital are with respiratory tract infections. As many as 70 percent of these are with upper respiratory tract infections including sore throat, cough, flu and fever, while 30 percent have lower respiratory tract infections including mild to moderate and severe pneumonia.

On average, the 2 hospitals are receiving 500 to 600 child patients daily of which nearly 400 are with complaints of respiratory tract infections, said Head of Paediatrics Department at Rawalpindi Medical College Professor Dr. Rai Muhammad Asghar while talking to 'The News' on Monday [15 Dec 2014]. He added that the paeds departments in the 2 hospitals are admitting around 50 child patients daily. We are admitting the patients who are suffering from severe pneumonia, he said.

It is important that the BBH has a capacity of 95 beds in its paeds department while the paeds department in HFH has a capacity of 120 beds. 'The News' has learnt that the bed occupancy rate in the 2 paeds departments at the 2 hospitals is more than 200 per cent as the departments are keeping 2 to 3 patients on almost all beds. When asked, Dr. Rai said the paeds departments at the HFH and BBH are following a unique policy and do not refuse admission to any child patient in need of it. Majority of admitted child patients at the paeds departments particularly below one year of age are suffering from severe pneumonia and are on oxygen therapy, he said. He explained that these patients need to be kept under continuous observation, and keeping this in mind, they are not refusing admission to any child patient suffering from severe pneumonia.

He said the incidence of both upper and lower respiratory tract infections among children can be avoided if parents take proper preventive measures well in time. The most important precautionary measure is that parents should avoid exposure of children to extreme cold, particularly in the morning and at night, he said. Children should be kept in warm places and their rooms should be kept well ventilated, said Dr. Rai. He added that children should not be exposed to any kind of smoke and dusty environment. To avoid upper and lower respiratory tract infections, it is a must to protect children from cold by using warm clothing while infants should be breastfed at least for 2 years. Parents should avoid children from getting wet to avoid pneumonia and the environment of the children should be kept clean, said Dr. Rai.

[Byline: Muhammad Qasim]

