[Pneumonia is the leading infectious cause of death in children worldwide, especially in low-income countries, and accounts for up to 19 percent of all deaths of children under 5 years old (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18545744). Most cases of childhood pneumonia occur in South Asia (India and Pakistan) and China (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18545744). Childhood pneumonia is usually caused by either viruses or bacteria. Bacterial causes of childhood pneumonia include _Streptococcus pneumoniae_, _Haemophilus influenzae_, _Staphylococcus aureus_, _Mycoplasma pneumoniae_, and _Chlamydophila pneumoniae_. However, most lower respiratory tract disease in children is viral in origin. The most common are respiratory syncytial virus or RSV, parainfluenza viruses, and influenza virus, which occur in the colder months of the year. Enteroviruses, such as enterovirus D68, occurs during the warmer summer months. Many of these potentially fatal childhood infections can be prevented, as they are caused by influenza viruses, _S. pneumoniae_ or _H. influenzae_ for which an effective vaccine is available. In addition, pneumonia caused by bacteria can be treated with antibiotics, but only 1/3rd of children with pneumonia are said to receive the antibiotics they need (http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs331/en/).

RSV causes both upper and lower respiratory infection (pneumonia and bronchiolitis) in children. RSV is a very contagious and the most common cause of bronchiolitis (inflammation of the small airways in the lung) and pneumonia in children younger than age 1 in the US. Almost all children are infected with the virus by 2 years of age. RSV spreads rapidly among children during outbreaks. Even after recovery, infants and children can continue to spread the virus for 1 to 3 weeks. Risk factors for RSV pneumonia are undernutrition, indoor air pollution, low birth weight, crowding and lack of measles immunization (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2647437/). In infants and very young children, RSV can be severe and require hospitalization. Some children with severe RSV are treated with an aerosolized drug called ribavirin. There is no vaccine to prevent RSV infection, but palivizumab, a monoclonal antibody, is used to prevent RSV infections during RSV season in infants and young children who have a higher risk for serious illness caused by RSV.

One or more of these viruses, especially RSV, is likely to be involved in the Pakistan outbreak. However, more detailed clinical, epidemiologic and microbiologic information would be needed to clarify the situation.

Holy Family Hospital (https://plus.google.com/101797232289693192254/about?hl=en) and Benazir Bhutto Hospital (https://plus.google.com/106344485355447283341/about?hl=en) are in the city of Rawalpindi, Pakistan. Rawalpindi is located 14 km (9 miles) south of the capital city of Islamabad, in the province of Punjab. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3046969,825.]
